    "updated_at": "2017-05-10T12:15:03Z",
    "body": "@dpatra but if you do something like this\r\n`if (startMinimized == true){\r\nconsole.log('App is started by AutoLaunch');\r\nmainWindow.hide();\r\n}`\r\n\r\nit will result in the main window by blinking briefly before it got hidden again.\r\n\r\nAn other solution would be to make the app lunch in system tray by default and make your app a [single instance](https://github.com/electron/electron/blob/master/docs/api/app.md#appmakesingleinstancecallback).\r\n\r\n```Javascript\r\nconst shouldQuit = app.makeSingleInstance(() => {\r\n  // Someone tried to run a second instance, we should focus our window.\r\n  if (win) {\r\n    win.show()\r\n  }\r\n});\r\n\r\n// Don't show the window and create a tray instead\r\napp.on('ready', () => { \r\n  win = new BrowserWindow({ show: false }); \r\n  appIcon = new Tray(iconPath);\r\n  //show window on tray icon click etc....\r\n})\r\n ```\r\n\r\nThis will start the app as minimized tray when ms-windows starts. If the user clicks on a shortcut or the .exe it will show the app window.\r\n\r\nBut as a disadvantage the user has to click twice after a fresh install / downloading the .exe to open your app..."
